                <head>189. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a speech at a May Day rally in Havana on May 1, 1961, Cuban Premier <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Fidel Castro</persName> stated that there had been a
                    socialist revolution in Cuba and that Cuba was a socialist country. (<hi
                        rend="italic">The New York Times</hi>, May 2, 1961) On May 2 Department of
                    State press spokesman Lincoln White interpreted <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName>ʼs speech to mean that Cuba had openly become a member of
                    the “Sino-Soviet bloc.” He noted that <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName>ʼs use of the term socialist was consistent with usage
                    throughout the Communist bloc, where socialism was viewed as a stage in the
                    evolution toward Communism. In fact, White stated, Castroʼs speech made it
                    appear that “<persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> considers Cuba
                    further along the communist road than some other countries in the bloc.” (<hi
                        rend="italic">American Foreign Policy: Current Documents, 1961</hi>, pages
                    306-307)</p>
                <p>Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> confirmed this
                    interpretation in his replies to questions at a press conference at the
                    Department of State on May 4. <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>
                    <pb facs="0437" n="405" xml:id="pg_405"/> noted that Cuba had become, in
                        <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>ʼs own words, “a declared
                    member of the Sino-Soviet bloc.” <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>
                    described the development as a “setback” for the Western Hemisphere. He stated,
                    “the thing to do now is to draw a deep breath and look over the situation very
                    carefully and consider a wide range of problems involved and possible actions
                    which ought to be taken; and, most of all, to stay on the main road of
                    hemispheric development and hemispheric solidarity.” (Department of State <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, May 22, 1961, page 762)</p>
            </div>
